10/02/2023,748.685(a)(4) - Individual Standards Evaluated,Individual Standards Evaluated,No,12/15/2023,12/18/2023,Individual Standards Evaluated,High,Yes,"A child in care, who was identified as in ""active substance use"" was released to school, where the child then absconded. ","2nd Chance will continue to provide training to staff in order to achieve and display appropriate supervision while residents are under the facilitys care.  All RTC staff will become knowledgeable with appropriate supervision based off the youths history and current behaviors placed at the facility.  These trainings will be conducted pre-service employment, bi-annually, annually, and/or as needed.  The training information will be conducted and provided by RTC Administrator, RTC Treatment Director, LPC, and/or Case Manager as well through the DFPS portal, and approved vendors ( CPR/1st Aid/AED and PAPH/EBI)   These trainings will include but not limited to DFPS Runaway Prevention, Cultural Competency, Normalcy, Trauma Informed Care, Human Trafficking, Abuse and Neglect, Sexual Abuseinformation from Attachment A (if deemed necessary), and brief overview of the youths historical and/or current behaviors.  2nd Chance will maintain the confidentiality and HIPPA regulations for all residents and work closely with our partners to protect the physical, mental, and emotional wellbeing of residents entrusted to our care."
10/02/2023,748.685(a)(3) - Individual Standards Evaluated,Individual Standards Evaluated,No,12/15/2023,12/18/2023,Individual Standards Evaluated,High,Yes,Children in care brought marijuana into the facility and used it in the bathroom on multiple occasions. ,"Effective immediately, 2nd Chance will continue to maintain client and care giver ratio on each shift to not only ensure adequate supervision, but to also assure resident safety. 
 Staff will orient new residents and current residents placed in the facility to ensure the youth is knowledgeable and understands the rules on appropriate bodily searches and room searches.  These searches will be conducted to reduce the potential for contraband being brought into the facility as well as being thorough, but non-intrusive, search of each individual and their possessions.  These searches will occur when they arrive back to facility from any outdoor event such school, community events, family visitation, random room checks, etc.  The youths searches will include the individual emptying of their pockets, taking off their shoes, backpacks, their belongings, and lifting up and/or shaking their pant legs. The searches will not only be conducted when the youth return home but also completed of their room if there is reason to believe/suspension of possible drug usage or if it is possible that the youth may have contraband in their possession. 
Each time, a youth is search even if they refuse the search, the incident will be documented in the Personal and Room Search log which will include the date and time of search, a list of any unacceptable items were found throughout the search, and staffs signature who(m) conducted the search.  If any unacceptable items were discovered, the items will be confiscated, storage in a lock location, and the youths treatment team will be notified. The RTC team will await the treatments team directives on how to move forward with the contraband.   
"
